# Component architecture (Pulse UI)

## Clean JSX – no logic in JSX

**Never put business logic, conditions, or async work directly in JSX.** Extract to custom hooks; components receive data and callbacks as props.

```tsx
// ❌ BAD: Logic in JSX
<button onClick={async () => {
  setIsRetrying(true);
  try {
    await retrySubmission(submission.id);
    showToast('Success');
  } catch (error) { showToast(getErrorMessage(error)); }
  finally { setIsRetrying(false); }
}}>Retry</button>

// ✅ GOOD: Logic in hook, clean JSX
const { shouldShowRetry, isRetrying, handleRetry } = useSubmissionActions(submission);
return shouldShowRetry && (
  <button onClick={() => handleRetry(submission.id)} disabled={isRetrying}>Retry</button>
);
```

## Feature folder structure

Each screen/feature is self-contained under `src/screens/FeatureName/`:

```
FeatureName/
├── FeatureName.tsx              # Main component (clean JSX)
├── FeatureName.interface.ts     # Types
├── FeatureName.constants.ts    # Feature constants (not global)
├── index.ts
├── hooks/                       # useQuery, useMutation, actions, derived state
├── components/                 # Subcomponents
└── utils/                      # Feature-specific helpers (optional)
```

**App-level:** Screens in `src/screens/`; shared in `src/components/`, `src/constants/`, `src/services/`, `src/stores/`, `src/hooks/`, `src/utils/`, `src/types/`. **Feature-first:** constants, utils, types live **inside the feature** unless truly shared across 2+ features. See `feature-first-abstraction.mdc`.

## Screen component pattern

1. Imports (React, types, constants, components, hooks, styles)
2. Component: call custom hooks (data, actions), simple derived state, effects for cleanup only, then **clean JSX**
3. Styles at bottom (CSS module)

Use `useQuery`/`useMutation` in hooks under `hooks/`; screen uses those hooks and renders. Error UI: show message + Retry (or clear path forward), not only dismiss.
